<subSubSection type="nomenclature">
<paragraph pageNumber="15">
Genre 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:230413" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Plagiolepis" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Plagiolepis (Acantholepis) rothneyi subsp. sundaica Emery" lsidName-HNS="Plagiolepis (Acantholepis) rothneyi subsp. sundaica Emery" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Acantholepis">Acantholepis</taxonomicName>
Mayr.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="description">
<paragraph pageNumber="15">
Ce genre parait au premier abord tres facile a distinguer des 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:24789" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Plagiolepis" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Plagiolepis Mayr" lsidName-HNS="Plagiolepis Mayr" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Plagiolepis</taxonomicName>
, par l'epinotum tres anguleux au-dessus des stomates et l'ecaille ordinairement bicuspide, mais les passages au sous-genre 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:223956" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Plagiolepis" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Uploaded - Plagiolepis (Anacantholepis)" lsidName-HNS="Uploaded - Plagiolepis (Anacantholepis)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Anacantholepis">Anacantholepis</taxonomicName>
sont frequents et alors la distinction ne repose plus que sur le developpement accentue des ocelles, la variabilite de la taille ou la forme plus anguleuse de l'epinotum.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
